name: Darling Downs Robocup
bleachedEventDetails:
Join us for a Robocup Teacher Workshop, designed to provide a beginner/refresher training for key Robocup challenges. This session will cover:
	•	Line Rescue – Basic and advanced strategies
	•	Maze – Understanding the challenge and programming techniques
	•	OnStage – Creative robotics performance guidance
	•	Soccer (on request) – If there’s interest, we can include an introduction to Robocup Soccer

This workshop is a great opportunity to learn, collaborate and prepare for upcoming competitions. A teacher and student workshop is also planned for May (date TBC).

If you’re interested in attending or supporting, please let us know. We’d love to have you involved!

Some refreshments (actual food! Not just biscuits and tea/coffee) will be offered to keep you going through the evening.

name: DD Intro to RoboCup Junior –Maze,Line and Onstage
bleachedEventDetails:
Introduction to RoboCup Junior – Maze, Line and OnStage (4pm-6pm workshop then networking/social drinks 6-7pm)

This workshop is a practical introduction to the RoboCup Junior competition, designed for teachers/mentors/parents who are new to RoboCup or who want greater confidence supporting student teams.

The session will cover the three core events offered at the regional level: Rescue Line, Rescue Maze and OnStage. Teachers will be guided through how each event works, what students are expected to do and how schools can get started with minimal equipment.

Participants will:
	•	Gain a clear understanding of the Maze, Line and OnStage challenges and rules
	•	Explore example robots and typical sensors used in each event
	•	Take part in hands-on activities with robots and basic programming
	•	Learn how to structure sessions, manage teams and scaffold student learning
	•	Receive practical tips for preparing teams for the upcoming RoboCup season

This is a supportive, hands-on workshop with a strong focus on building teacher confidence. No prior RoboCup experience is required. The session is suitable for primary and secondary teachers involved in Technologies, robotics clubs or extracurricular STEM programs.

Please consider staying after the session to have a free drink (or two) and connect with other teachers and mentors. RoboCup Junior is strongest when we can collaborate, share ideas and support one another throughout the season. This will be a great opportunity to build relationships, ask questions and strengthen local networks.

The Queensland Society for IT in Education (QSITE) provides support for teachers to integrate technology in schools. The Toowoomba chapter of QSITE is proud to support RoboCup Junior and is providing complimentary refreshments for a networking session after the RoboCup Junior workshops.

name: DD Introduction to RoboCup Junior – Soccer
bleachedEventDetails:
Introduction to RoboCup Junior – Soccer (4-6pm workshop then 6-7pm networking/social drinks)
This workshop provides a practical introduction to RoboCup Junior Soccer, aimed at teachers, mentors or parents who are new to the Soccer competition or who want to build confidence supporting student teams.

The session focuses on how RoboCup Junior Soccer works at the regional level, including the rules, field setup and the core concepts students need to succeed. Teachers will explore how robots detect the ball, move accurately on the field and work within the constraints of the competition.

Participants will:
	•	Develop a clear understanding of RoboCup Junior Soccer rules and match structure
	•	Learn how robots locate and track the infrared ball
	•	Explore drive systems, sensors and basic control strategies used in Soccer robots
	•	Take part in hands-on activities with robots and simple programming examples
	•	Gain practical advice for setting up teams and running training sessions at school

This is a hands-on, teacher-friendly workshop designed to demystify RoboCup Junior Soccer and help schools confidently prepare teams for the upcoming competition season. No prior RoboCup Soccer experience is required.

Please consider staying after the session to have a free drink (or two) and connect with other teachers and mentors. RoboCup Junior is strongest when we can collaborate, share ideas and support one another throughout the season. This will be a great opportunity to build relationships, ask questions and strengthen local networks.

The Queensland Society for IT in Education (QSITE) provides support for teachers to integrate technology in schools. The Toowoomba chapter of QSITE is proud to support RoboCup Junior and is providing complimentary refreshments for a networking session after the RoboCup Junior workshops.

name: Darling Downs Regional Robocup Junior 2026
bleachedEventDetails:
The RoboCup Junior season is back and shaping up to be one of the most exciting yet. The Darling Downs Regional Competition brings together students, teachers and mentors from across the region to celebrate creativity, problem-solving and real-world robotics.

Teams will design, build and program autonomous robots to tackle authentic challenges across the RoboCup Junior categories. From precise line following and rescue scenarios to complex maze navigation and creative performance, students will be pushed to think critically, collaborate and innovate under competition conditions.

This event is about more than trophies. It is a supportive, high-energy environment where students share ideas, learn from one another and gain confidence in engineering, coding and systems thinking. Whether teams are brand new or highly experienced, RoboCup Junior provides meaningful challenge and genuine excitement for all participants.

The 2026 Darling Downs Regional Competition will be hosted at Fairholme College, providing a fantastic venue for teams, judges and supporters to come together for a full day of robotics action.

We look forward to welcoming returning teams and new schools to another great RoboCup Junior season. Start building, start testing and get ready to compete.
